{
  "local_port": 50152,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "I am using a Moto G, and it failed to download the OTA update of Android due to a network error. Now what can I do to get it updated?",
  "response": "If your Moto G failed to download the OTA (Over-The-Air) update due to a network error, don\u2019t worry. Here are some steps you can take to successfully update your device:\n\n### 1. **Check Your Internet Connection**\n   - Ensure you have a stable and strong Wi-Fi connection. OTA updates require a reliable internet connection.\n   - If possible, switch to a different Wi-Fi network or ensure your current one is working properly.\n   - Avoid public or slow networks, as they may cause interruptions during the download.\n\n### 2. **Restart Your Device**\n   - Restart your Moto G to refresh the system and clear any temporary glitches.\n   - After restarting, try downloading the update again.\n\n### 3. **Clear Google Play Services Cache**\n   - Go to **Settings > Apps & Notifications > See all apps**.\n   - Find and tap **Google Play Services**.\n   - Select **Storage & Cache**, then tap **Clear Cache**.\n   - Retry the OTA update.\n\n### 4. **Check Available Storage**\n   - Ensure your device has enough free storage space for the update (at least 1-2 GB is recommended).\n   - Go to **Settings > Storage** to check available space and delete unnecessary files or apps if needed.\n\n### 5. **Manually Check for Updates**\n   - Go to **Settings > System > System updates**.\n   - Tap **Check for update** to see if the OTA update is still available for download.\n\n### 6. **Use Cellular Data (if Wi-Fi is unavailable)**\n   - If Wi-Fi isn\u2019t working, you can use cellular data, but ensure you have a sufficient data plan.\n   - Go to **Settings > System > System updates**, and select **Download using mobile data** (if available).\n\n### 7. **Reset Network Settings**\n   - If the issue persists, reset your network settings:\n     - Go to **Settings > System > Reset options > Reset Wi-Fi, mobile & Bluetooth**.\n     - Note: This will erase saved Wi-Fi networks and Bluetooth pairings, so you\u2019ll need to reconnect to your Wi-Fi afterward.\n\n### 8. **Update via a Computer (Advanced)**\n   - If the OTA update fails repeatedly, you can manually update your Moto G using a computer and the **Motorola Device Manager** or **Lenovo Smart Assistant** (for newer Motorola devices).\n   - Download the tool on your computer, connect your phone via USB, and follow the on-screen instructions to update.\n\n### 9. **Contact Motorola Support**\n   - If none of the above steps work, reach out to Motorola\u2019s customer support for assistance. They may provide additional troubleshooting steps or inform you if there\u2019s an issue with the update itself.\n\n### 10. **Wait and Try Again Later**\n   - Sometimes, OTA updates are rolled out in phases, and server issues can cause temporary failures. Wait a few hours or a day and try again.\n\nBy following these steps, you should be able to successfully update your Moto G to the latest Android version.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
